      "side": 1,
      "message": "This is specifically for main() which wouldn\u0027t have a return expression, but might have:\n\n  if (x) { foo(); return; } else { bar(); return; }\n\nThis would become\n\n  if (x) { foo(); return *_out; } else { bar(); return *_out; } return *_out;\n\nTechnically the extraneous return doesn\u0027t actually hurt anything. Maybe we don\u0027t need this check at all; I was trying to answer the FIXME but maybe it\u0027s not worth the added complexity. You can have `return *_out; return *_out;` at the end of a program and it compiles fine.\n\n(I just checked and even with -Wunreachable-code, `return *_out; return *_out;` doesn\u0027t complain! Neither does  `return *_out; return Outputs{};`! It only triggers the warning if you put something else between the two returns, like `int foo \u003d 0;`.)",
